AGI - From tomorrow, 31 March, Bulgaria and Romania join the Schengen area of free movement of persons and goods, bringing to 29 the number of countries included: controls at maritime and air borders will be abolished. The historic decision on the entry of the two countries was taken last December by the European Council. The President of the Commission, Ursula von der Leyen, was delighted today with the new success of the two countries and the European Union: "It is a historical moment for the Schengen area, the largest free movement in the world. Together, we build a stronger and more united Europe for all our citizens." Since 2011, the Commission has considered that Bulgaria and Romania fulfilled all conditions to become an integral part of the Schengen area, one of the most appreciated achievements by citizens of the European Union. Started in 1985 as an intergovernmental project between Germany, Belgium, France, Luxembourg and the Netherlands, it expanded to include almost all the countries of the European Union. Cyprus and Ireland are still excluded, while some non-EU countries are: Iceland, Liechtenstein, Norway and Switzerland.&nbsp;
&nbsp;
The entry of Romania and Bulgaria into the Schengen area, which took place at midnight local time and therefore at 23 in Italy on 30 March, does not include road access to the two countries: Austria has indeed vetoed the opening of frontiers by land, fearing an increase in flows of asylum seekers. To be penalized by the lack of openness of road frontiers are mainly the transporters, forced to long waits. The trade unions remember that for example "only 3% of Bulgarian goods are transported by air and by sea, the remaining 97% travel by wheel". In any case, both Sofia and Bucharest warned: you will not return. This is an "irreversible process", as the Romanian Interior Minister Catalin Predoiu recently declared, calling for the completion of this year.&nbsp;

